    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_204903"><b>By Dawn</b><br />
By Digo<br />
<br />
By dawn, everyone in this tavern will be dead. It won’t be for my lack of trying, either.<br />
<br />
The front door swings open with a blast of ice storm air, and even the fireplace shivers from the cold. We’re stuck in an ice storm right in the middle of absolutely nowhere between the mountain pass, and there’s a demon loose in the village.<br />
<br />
The outrider’s beard drips with ice, like how a snowman looks after the rain. Must be frozen solid. He shakes and stumbles over to the fire, stammering about the bodies, the bodies. How the pass is closed.<br />
<br />
<br />
I try not to listen as these thugs debate what’s a perfectly hopeless predicament.<br />
<br />
His mail is rusted. Leather hasn’t been oiled in weeks. I’d be surprised if his sword still held an edge. Regan, the leader of this little mercenary band of dunces, he’ll be the first to go. <br />
<br />
I’d point this out to him, but I don’t like delivering bad news. I hear so much of it. That and he crammed an oily rag into my mouth and bound my hands because this is all my fault because I am a mage, obviously.<br />
<br />
I’d point out to him that this is all easily preventable. That a demon doesn’t need to scream through this moldering oak inn with terrible roofing, slaughtering everyone. <br />
<br />
I’d point this out to him and his dagger-happy underlings, but they think I’m responsible for unleashing this fiend on the village, and, in a way, I probably am.<br />
<br />
My name is Renhold. My father is a gravedigger. I visit him once a year, but even then, it’s a tense, uncomfortable time together. When your own father scratches runes of protection into the doorpost when you come to visit, well, that’s not a pleasant sign.<br />
<br />
My mother, well, I’m not sure how she died, but if I listen long enough, I’m sure she’ll tell me.<br />
<br />
The men are terrified and screaming, mostly at each other. Something dark and cold just passed by the window, and when they looked, they saw a face in the frosty blackness. It was the demon. Checking in on me.<br />
<br />
<br />
I’d call out the demon and bind him, but an oiled rag that makes me retch when I swallow and taste the grime keeps me from using magic. I’d take out the gag, but my wrists are bleeding from the coarse rope binding my hands impossibly tight to this chair. And Regan, the leader of this mercenary band hired to track me down and hang me; he doesn’t believe for a second that I’d protect them from the demon.<br />
<br />
Dealing with infernal princes of the netherworld isn’t something I make a habit of. I try to avoid it actually. Magic tends to get you in these sorts of predicaments.<br />
<br />
It’s not that I chose to study magic. My mother certainly wouldn’t approve. Maybe one day, when I’m sorting through the thousands of voices from dead people that echo in my head, I’ll find my mother. <br />
<br />
As long as I can remember, the echoes have been there. Most fathers take some pride in passing on their trade to sons. Not mine. Imagine a gravedigger trying to hide death from his only son. So one day, when he finally took me out to the burial fields past the monastery, I heard them.<br />
<br />
I was helping him clear the mulch and topsoil for a new grave – the coughing sickness was bad that year – when I heard a shifting and sliding and screaming of voices. This frightened me, of course. I dropped the shovel and hid behind my father, clutching at his leg. <br />
<br />
About now, I’d hide behind my father too, if I knew a demon was prowling outside in the ice storm. If I knew that the storm hadn’t let up in two days. If I knew that slowly, the demon was feeding on villagers. So I can’t really blame Regan and these mercenaries and whoever hired them to track me down for being afraid.<br />
<br />
I’d save them if I could. I always try to save everyone.<br />
<br />
The voices didn’t stop. Like a crowded marketplace or inn, I could drown them out. Ignore them. I learned that if I listened hard, focused and tried to place names and faces with the sounds, I could find people. Like eavesdropping on a conversation across the room.<br />
<br />
When I find these voices and pull them out from the echo storm, they tell me what happened. How they died. What they left unfinished. Who killed them. Who they loved. Sometimes who they loved killed them. Sometimes, terrible crimes I couldn’t shake from my head. Crimes that I’d sit up in the night shaking, wishing that they would get out of my head. My mother worried about me. Maybe the worrying is what killed her.<br />
<br />
It wasn’t long after I learned to sort through these voices, to find the ones that didn’t terrify me, that didn’t give me shaking cold sweats, that I found Tiberian. A mage.<br />
<br />
Regan slaps me across the face with a mailed fist and for a second, I stop wondering how can I save these people. He barks in my face, cursing me for unleashing this monster on the good people of wherever I am. He hits me again, but I’m starting not to feel it. When you hear a thousand other people’s memories and emotions and agony every day, your own pain seems a bit trivial.<br />
<br />
The mercenaries have their swords drawn. They’re wrapping table and chair legs with rags, making torches. They’re terrified, and right in the middle of this sprawling commons room, I’m slumped forward in a chair, closing my eyes, trying to tune out their fear, and waiting for it to all be over. There’s not much I can do at this point besides bury the fallen.<br />
<br />
Getting out of these ropes might be tricky, but the demon will probably help… once they’re all dead, of course. The demon will want to move on to the next village, and he figures that this will happen again. That ignorant louts will let him run wild, keeping me powerless to rein him in.<br />
<br />
Tiberian was a mage. Probably a little insane. He died lonely because he never figured out that magic isn’t the end-all-be-all of existence. Tiberian died alone, rotting in his cabin because he never took on an apprentice. The man could summon demons, command elementals, and transmute stone to water, but he couldn’t make anyone love him. Or even tolerate him.<br />
<br />
So when I found Tiberian in the storm of echoes that bangs away at my head every waking moment, I felt sorry for him. I just left our home and started walking into the woods.<br />
<br />
A few hours before sundown, I found the cabin. The mage’s bones were still sitting upright in his rocking chair. I’d helped my father dig a few graves by now, so I wasn’t scared. And I knew him.<br />
<br />
So I swept up the mess. I put his books on the shelf. I dusted the cabin. And then it was just me and Tiberian. I sat across from his bones well past sundown, listening to his voice.<br />
<br />
This was more attention than anyone had shown him in a long time. To thank me, he told me secrets. He explained to me how I could use magic. When I had learned enough, he just left. I didn’t hear from him ever again.<br />
<br />
The room is getting cold. The fire is burning out. <br />
<br />
If I could just explain.<br />
<br />
If I could just let them know, I can help.<br />
<br />
I’ve been traveling with this demon for weeks. I reached through the still surface of a wellspring and the demon came screaming out. It splashed and slammed into the surface of the water like a bird crashing into the surface of a silver lake, finally free. <br />
<br />
The man who imprisoned the demon in this water so many years ago is dead, and it’s his voice that brought me this far. There’s a temple over the mountains. The priests can help me. I just have to get there without killing everyone along the way. <br />
<br />
This shouldn’t be my responsibility, but if I don’t help, then another little boy helping his father dig a grave is going to hear a voice in his head, begging to help catch a demon.<br />
<br />
Regan is holding a dagger to my neck when he pulls the rag out of my mouth. I cough and spit. <br />
<br />
Move and I stab you, he says. Help us kill this thing, and we’ll let you live a little longer.<br />
<br />
Not that it matters.<br />
<br />
I look up slowly. They’re all terrified. Weapons and fire don’t make up for stupidity.<br />
<br />
I can help, I say slowly. But first, you have to listen.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
